  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different jurisdictions:\n\n1. United States\n- Comprehensive Anti-Money Laundering (AML) regulations\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) as foundational legislation\n- Strict reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Significant criminal and civil penalties\n- Emphasis on international cooperation\n\n2. European Union\n- Unified regulatory framework through AML Directives\n- Centralized approach with consistent standards\n- Enhanced due diligence requirements\n- Focus on transparency and beneficial ownership\n- Collaborative cross-border enforcement mechanisms\n\n3. United Kingdom\n- Proceeds of Crime Act as primary legislation\n- Robust financial intelligence unit\n- Risk-based regulatory approach\n- Strong emphasis on financial sector compliance\n- Advanced technological monitoring systems\n\n4. Switzerland\n- Traditionally strict banking secrecy laws\n- Gradual evolution towards international transparency\n- Sophisticated compliance mechanisms\n- Balanced approach between privacy and regulatory oversight\n\n5. China\n- Increasingly stringent AML regulations\n- Central government control\n- Focus on preventing capital flight\n- Growing alignment with international standards\n\n6. Singapore\n- Advanced regulatory framework\n- High compliance standards\n- Proactive approach to financial crime prevention\n- Strategic international collaboration\n\nEach jurisdiction has unique nuances, but generally trending towards increased transparency and cooperation.",
